  <h1>Types of Civil Rights Violations</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Riley Chen (RC), Employment &amp; Civil Rights Practice Lead. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>Excessive force (Fourth and Fourteenth Amendment)</h2>
  <p>The most litigated &sect; 1983 claim. The objective reasonableness standard from <em>Graham v. Connor</em> (1989) governs: would a reasonable officer have used this level of force under the circumstances? Key factors: severity of crime, whether the suspect posed an immediate threat, whether they were resisting or fleeing. Fatal force cases bring the highest damages; even minor unnecessary force claims can survive qualified immunity.</p>
  <h2>Unlawful arrest and detention</h2>
  <p>An arrest without probable cause violates the Fourth Amendment. Wrongful conviction cases &mdash; where a person is imprisoned and later exonerated &mdash; produce the largest &sect; 1983 verdicts (sometimes tens of millions for years of wrongful imprisonment). Extended pretrial detention without probable cause also qualifies.</p>
  <h2>Unlawful searches and seizures</h2>
  <p>Warrantless searches without a recognized exception, searches that exceed the scope of a warrant, and unreasonable property seizures. Digital privacy (cell phone searches, GPS tracking) has been an active area after <em>Riley v. California</em> (2014) and <em>Carpenter v. United States</em> (2018).</p>
  <h2>First Amendment retaliation</h2>
  <p>Government action (arrest, demotion, prosecution) taken in retaliation for protected speech or association. Requires showing the protected activity was a substantial motivating factor in the adverse action. Common in cases involving journalists, public employees who spoke out, protesters, and people who filed complaints against police.</p>
  <h2>Due process violations</h2>
  <p>Procedural due process: deprivation of liberty or property without adequate process. Substantive due process: government action that shocks the conscience. The latter sets a high bar &mdash; negligence is not enough; deliberate indifference may be.</p>
  <h2>Equal protection</h2>
  <p>Government treatment based on race, sex, national origin, or other classification without adequate justification. Race discrimination by government actors (selective enforcement, discriminatory application of laws) is the most common equal protection claim.</p>
